    <h2>About Nick Turpin</h2>
 

  <p>I am primarily a �Street Photographer�, I make pictures in public places with as little interaction with my subject as possible. My aim is to observe and allow the world to reveal itself to me. The pictures are made very quickly with a small discreet camera. The resulting images are moments of everyday contemporary urban life that provide a mirror in which we may see the results of the decisions we have made as a society.</p>

<p>My Street Photography is financed by shooting projects for Advertising agencies and Design groups. I am generally asked to make Ads that look like the real life images that I make on the streets. The Art Directors I work with are attracted by the humour and spontaneity of my street pictures. The process of shooting an Ad Is far from spontaneous, it usually involves days of meetings and production followed by a shoot with models, lighting, make up, styling, props, location managers, assistants and catering. My shoot this year for Robinsons Barley Water required a crew of 22 people.</p>

<p>Like many artists, the struggle is to maintain the balance between the personal and commercial aspects of my work.</p>

<p>I also set up iN-PUBLiC in 2000 to provide a home for street photographers. </p>

